Crispy yet chewy, it's the ideal foundation for the flavorful toppings that burst with freshness. The sauce-to-cheese ratio? Spot on. editorialSummary.text: Legendary jazz musicians take the stage at this intimate club that also serves American eats.

text.text:
Renowned for its legendary live music performances. To ensure you catch your favorite show, it's wise to do your research on who's playing and book tickets in advance.

For a better view, consider opting for a table over standing at the bar, as the club's layout is rectangular. Tables are assigned on a first-come, first-served basis, so arriving early increases your chances of securing a good spot. Keep in mind that if a table isn't fully occupied, strangers may be seated together to fill the space.

While cocktails are around $20 USD each, they're worth the splurge for their quality. Service is a bit slowly and the place guys busy, epically on weekends. Although the live music experience is vibrant and engaging, making it a must-do activity for visitors looking to immerse themselves in New York's rich music scene.

Whether you're a jazz enthusiast or simply seeking a memorable night out, catching a show at the Blue Note is an experience that encapsulates the essence of the city's vibrant culture. From the electrifying atmosphere to the world-class musicianship, it's an unforgettable journey into the heart of jazz.

Amazing restaurant, one of the best sushi I had in my life (and prices were not bad!). Would recommend and will come back.
With my wife we went for a Saturday dinner with reservation. We arrive 20 minutes earlier and we were able to be sited early at the counter. This is another restaurant we saw recommended at the Michelin guide.

Food was incredible: we tried the “small” sushi menu (at $49/person) which consisted on a Salmon tataki, 9 pieces of sushi and 2 sushi rolls. At the beginning I thought we were going to finish hungry give the word “small” on the menu but it was more than ok (and I eat a lot!).

Salmon tataki was good but not great, but you could tell how fresh the fish was. Loved that it was slightly grilled on the top.
I loved the sushi selection: 9 different pieces of salmon, tuna, yellowfish, among other fishes combined with different sauces which harmoniously enhanced the flavor. The best sushi I had.
Sushi rolls were also amazing (perhaps the highlight of the menu). I had the oyster mushroom roll and the spicy tuna one. Both were very crispy on the outside with an amazing combination of flavors, however the one that my wife order (unagui) was the absolute best.

At the end we order the matcha pudding which was actually pretty good. Not too bitter and not to sweet – very well balanced.
Service was fast (perhaps way too fast) and attentive.

Atmosphere was very Japanese inspired of course. What was a bit of a disappointment was that we sited at the counter, and we expected that the cooking was going to be happening there but there was only one guy cutting the fishes.

text.text:
We stopped by Banter for brunch on a Saturday around 11am and were surprised the wait was already over an hour. In total we waited nearly an hour and a half and while the food and drinks were tasty, I’m not sure I would wait that long again.

We were seated inside and, despite it being pretty cold outside, wished we were seated in the outdoor seating area. The inside is quite cozy and loud since the drinks station is dead center, so you have to tune out the clanging and crashing of cups and plates. The outside area was much quieter despite being near the street and cars.

We ordered the banter bowl with grilled chicken, and the green vitality and fresh start juices.

The banter bowl tasted very fresh and light while still being very filling. The miso ponzu dressing tied all the fresh ingredients together and definitely made the fish. The chicken was slightly rough and dry.

The green vitality was my favorite juice and tasted very green, with particular notes of celery. The fresh start was quite tart and had a nice hint of ginger, but wasn’t for me.

Overall I left Banter feeling satisfied, refreshed, and full enough to continue my day in the city.

text.text:
Roscioli in NYC is an authentic Italian haven that effortlessly transports its guests straight to the cobblestone streets of Italy with its old-school vibe and impeccable culinary offerings. From the moment you step inside, you’re enveloped in an ambiance that is both warmly inviting and unmistakably Italian.

The wine list at Roscioli is a testament to the restaurant’s commitment to quality and variety, boasting an extensive selection that can satisfy even the most discerning of oenophiles. It perfectly complements the menu, which is a celebration of Italian flavors brought to life with skill and passion.

Our culinary journey began with the flatbread accompanied by pesto, a simple dish that was elevated to extraordinary through the freshness and strength of its flavors. Then we had the fried rice ball which was also a stand out.  The chicken ravioli, served with a brown butter sauce, was another standout, offering a beautiful balance of textures and a richness that was satisfying without being overwhelming.

Dessert was the crowning glory of the meal - an olive oil cake that deserves every bit of its 5/5 rating. Its moist texture, nuanced flavor, and the perfect hint of olive oil made it an unforgettable end to an exceptional dining experience.

Roscioli is more than just a restaurant; it’s a destination for those in search of genuine Italian cuisine in NYC. Highly recommended for its atmospheric charm, outstanding food, and extensive wine list, Roscioli is a must-visit for anyone looking to indulge in the true essence of Italy.

text.text: Do you like blaring music featuring The Beach Boys and Credence Clear Water Revival while eating dinner at an outpost of a beloved Roman restaurant? Do you enjoy overcooked pasta? Do you appreciate being bluntly told you have to leave in 60 minutes by a host who lacks grace and interpersonal skills while dressed as if she just rolled out of bed? Then perhaps Roscioli NYC is for you. A far cry from the original in Rome, Roscioli is a missed opportunity and a poor representation of the brand. The West Village restaurant itself is cute and stocked with some enticing Roman products, but plating and the way dishes are cooked are inconsistent; the service is just so brimming with attitude and indifference; the music is overwhelmingly loud - we can’t find enough reasons to return. Sigh.

We ate at the 8:30-Monday-night 5 course tasting and wine pairing.  We descended down an incredibly steep set of stairs with a door oddly at it's midpoint into the subterranean  dining room/enoteca. We had two of the four seats at the bar/prep counter.

The service was prompt and servers were friendly. The food was good, tasted bright, and left me feeling full. Maybe the rigatoni could have been cooked 75 seconds longer. The wine pairings were fun, inventive, and showcased underrated and lesser-known Italian varietals. Definitely felt like a place to "be seen", and "be cool". Whatever.

We enjoyed our experience, but it was more fun in Rome a few years back. Welcome to the neighborhood!  Grazie e ci vediamo presto!

While they are indeed fairly good, they were underwhelming. They didn't feel like anything you couldn't whip up yourself and often you couldn't taste some of the ingredients they were supposed to have in them. They also were overly expensive for how much you get and their quality.

The atmosphere was fun but cramped, dark, and not the most comfortable. It definitely feels like being wedged into an underground wooden keg style room. Lots of dark wood. The service is simply counter service which isn't anything special.

An enjoyable experience but honestly I wouldn't come back a second time.

text.text:
I recently visited Jane's Restaurant for breakfast and had a mixed experience. Here's a detailed breakdown:

Starters:

Deviled Eggs: These were decent, but not particularly noteworthy.

Honey Biscuits: These were a highlight! Light, fluffy, and with a touch of sweetness from the honey, they were a delicious way to start the meal.

Main Course:

Farmhouse Frittata: Unfortunately, this dish fell short of expectations. While it included all the classic ingredients - egg, ham, cheese, and breakfast potatoes - it lacked any real flavor. It desperately needed seasoning, and I found myself relying heavily on the salt and pepper shakers to bring some life to the dish.
Drinks:

Coffee: Thankfully, the coffee was good and provided a welcome pick-me-up.
Overall:

Jane's breakfast had its ups and downs. While the honey biscuits and coffee were good, the unseasoned frittata was a disappointment. If I were to return, I'd definitely give the biscuits another try, but I would hesitate to order the frittata again.
